l, Biratnagar, Nepal</aff><aff id="aff10"><label>9</label>Singapore National Eye Centre, Singapore</aff><aff id="aff11"><label>10</label>Singapore Eye Research Institute, The Academia, Singapore, Singapore</aff><aff id="aff12"><label>11</label>Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Sciences, Academic Clinical Program, Duke-NUS Medical School, Singapore, Singapore</aff><aff id="aff13"><label>12</label>Lee Kong Chian School of Medicine, Singapore</aff><aff id="aff14"><label>13</label>Moorfields Eye Hospital, NHS Foundation Trust, London, UK</aff><author-notes><corresp id="cor1"><bold>Correspondence to:</bold> Prof. Rupesh Agrawal, Tan Tock Seng Hospital, National Healthcare Group Eye Institute, Singapore. E-mail: <email xlink:href="rupeshttsh@gmail.com">rupeshttsh@gmail.com</email></corresp></author-notes><!--Fake ppub date generated by PMC from publisher
					pub-date/@pub-type='epub-ppub'--><pub-date pub-type="ppub"><month>5</month><year>2024</year></pub-date><pub-date pub-type="epub"><day>20</day><month>4</month><year>2024</year></pub-date><volume>72</volume><issue>Suppl 3</issue><fpage>S473</fpage><lpage>S481</lpage><history><date date-type="received"><day>14</day><month>8</month><year>2023</year></date><date date-type="rev-recd"><day>10</day><month>11</month><year>2023</year></date><date date-type="accepted"><day>03</day><month>1</month><year>2024</year></date></history><permissions><copyright-statement>Copyright: &#x000a9; 2024 Indian Journal of Ophthalmology</copyright-statement><copyright-year>2024</copyright-year><license><ali:license_ref xmlns:ali="http://www.niso.org/schemas/ali/1.0/" specific-use="textmining" content-type="ccbyncsalicense">https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/</ali:license_ref><license-p>This is an open access journal, and articles are distributed under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 License, which allows others to remix, tweak, and build upon the work non-commercially, as long as appropriate credit is given and the new creations are licensed under the identical terms.</license-p></license></permissions><abstract><sec id="st1"><title>Purpose:</title><p>To evaluate rural community-based eye care models from the perspective of community ophthalmology experts and suggest sustainable technological solutions for enhancing rural eye care delivery.</p></sec><sec id="st2"><title>Methods:</title><p>A semi-structured descriptive survey, using close-ended and open-ended questions, was administered to the experts in community ophthalmology sourced through purposive sampling. The survey was self-administered and was facilitated through online platforms or in-person meetings. Uniform questions were presented to all participants, irrespective of their roles.</p></sec><sec id="st3"><title>Results:</title><p>Surveyed participants (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic> = 22 with 15 from India and 7 from Nepal) in high-volume tertiary eye hospitals faced challenges with resources and rural outreach. Participants had mixed satisfaction with pre-operative screening and theatre resources. Delayed presentations and inexperienced surgeons contributed to the surgery complications. Barriers to rural eye care included resource scarcity, funding disparities, and limited infrastructure. In rural/peri-urban areas 87% of participants agreed with providing primary eye care services, with more than 60% of the experts not in agreement with the makeshift center model of eye care delivery. Key components for an effective eye care model are sustainability, accessibility, affordability, and quality. These can be bolstered through a healthcare management platform and a human-chain supply distribution system.</p></sec><sec id="st4"><title>Conclusion:</title><p>Tailored interventions are crucial for rural eye care, emphasizing the need for stronger human resources, optimized funding, and community awareness. Addressing challenges pertinent to delayed presentation and surgical training is vital to minimizing complications, especially with advanced cataracts. Enhancements in rural eye care demand a comprehensive approach prioritizing accessibility, affordability, and consistent quality.</p></sec></abstract><kwd-group><kwd>Community ophthalmology</kwd><kwd>eye care</kwd><kwd>eye care barrier</kwd><kwd>perspectives</kwd><kwd>primary eye care</kwd></kwd-group></article-meta></front><body><p>Globally, there are 1.1 billion people with vision loss, a number projected to reach 1.7 billion in the next 30 years according to the International Agency for the Prevention of Blindness (IAPB). Ninety percent of these people live in low- and middle-income countries, where 90% of visual loss is preventable and treatable.[<xref rid="R1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>] In 2020, an estimated 78.8 million people aged 50+ had moderate to severe vision impairment, due to cataracts.[<xref rid="R2" ref-type="bibr">2</xref>] Cataract continues to be the principal cause of blindness in populations aged 50 + years due to local barriers such as lack of transportation or people to accompany patients to appointments.[<xref rid="R3" ref-type="bibr">3</xref><xref rid="R4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>] Thus, community-based eye care initiatives are crucial in rural areas to reduce preventable blindness and improve access to eye care.</p><p>Primary eye care in rural and peri-urban areas, according to the World Health Organization (WHO),[<xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>] involves community workers identifying and referring people with low vision to higher-level services, and offering advice on lifestyle and behavioral changes to improve their eye health.[<xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref><xref rid="R6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>] Secondary eye care is at the district level and includes assessing visual function, refraction testing, prescribing low-vision devices, providing guidance on optical interventions, and referring to tertiary services when appropriate.[<xref rid="R4" ref-type="bibr">4</xref><xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>] Tertiary eye care involves advanced service by trained professionals at a well-equipped eye clinic or hospital.[<xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref><xref rid="R6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>]</p><p>Various eye care delivery models exist for rural and peri-urban areas, each with unique strengths and weaknesses. The Aravind model,[<xref rid="R7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>] successful in densely populated areas, may not be feasible in low-density rural communities due to resource constraints and administration requirements. Developing a more implementable eye care model is urgent, especially for Africa and other regions, with community ophthalmology having limitations. Empowering rural communities to sustain quality eye care independently is important. This study aims to examine existing models, gather perspectives from healthcare workers and experts, and propose practical and sustainable technological solutions for rural eye care. We also aim to highlight strengths and weaknesses, personal experiences, and identify areas of improvement. The perspective seeks to build a common understanding to address public health programs more effectively, proposing a standardized solution for delivering eye care in rural areas.</p><sec sec-type="methods" id="sec1-1"><title>Methods</title><p><italic toggle="yes">Survey questionnaire:</italic> We used a semi-structured survey with both close-ended and open-ended questions in the English language. The survey questionnaires were finalized and validated with inputs from global healthcare experts in the field of community ophthalmology (AS, TR, and HT). Based on the inputs received from these global healthcare experts, the survey form was revised several times (see <xref rid="APP1" ref-type="app">Appendix A</xref> for drafts and final version).</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Survey participants:</italic> Survey participants include physicians (ophthalmologists) and administrators (field workers) at rural eye hospitals in India and Nepal. The survey participants were identified through purposive sampling from community ophthalmology groups such as the Asia Pacific Academy of Ophthalmology and the IAPB and based on their achievements and publications related to community ophthalmology.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Survey administration:</italic> The survey was conducted by inviting participants via email for an online survey during November&#x02013;December 2022. Additionally, participants were provided the option to complete the survey through assisted Zoom interviews, with RL transcribing the physicians&#x02019; responses directly into the online survey form. CognitoForms software (CognitoForms, V2, June 2022, Columbia) was utilized for administering the survey, and responses were gathered over a two-month period. All participants, regardless of their positions, were required to answer the same set of questions in the survey, with no grading based on participant experience or expertise. In cases where participants encountered difficulties in completing the survey, RL conducted supplementary online or in-person interviews to assist in the completion of the questionnaire.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Survey questionnaire details:</italic> The questionnaire was designed to describe healthcare workers/physicians&#x02019; and experts&#x02019; region of practice, hospital profile, resources, practice patterns, community ophthalmology involvement, and opinions about areas that need improvement in current eye care models for rural and peri-urban areas. In particular, survey participants were first asked for details regarding their region of practice and roles in the hospital. They were then asked questions to profile their surgical practice (if applicable&#x02014;only for surgeons) and asked to describe their typical pre-operative, intra-operative, and post-operative cataract surgery workflows. The survey participants were prompted to rate their agreement with statements regarding the current state of eye care delivery and eye care models on a 5-point Likert scale. Finally, the last part of the survey included open-ended questions regarding where physicians believe improvements can be made to community ophthalmology in rural settings, and how to best ensure sustainable eye care delivery and positive patient outcomes. The open-ended questions were designed to build on our quantitative findings by expanding on physicians&#x02019; thoughts and perspectives about whether we are having the impact we intend to have in these communities and where improvements need to be made based on their personal experiences.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Ethical approval and consent to participate:</italic> This study was reviewed and acknowledged as exempt by the institutional review board of a tertiary eye care institute in Central India. The research methods used in this study adhere to the Declaration of Helsinki. Completion of the survey included the provision of informed consent to participate.</p></sec><sec sec-type="results" id="sec1-2"><title>Results</title><p><italic toggle="yes">Survey participant profiles:</italic> We collected survey responses from 22 experts in the field of community ophthalmology (15 from India and 7 from Nepal) [see <xref rid="APP1" ref-type="app">Appendix A</xref>]. The broad range of roles served by our survey respondents demonstrates that they are involved in all aspects of providing services in community ophthalmology, from regulatory work to building community awareness to providing medical care and surgical expertise [<xref rid="APP2" ref-type="app">Appendix B</xref>]. The category of &#x0201c;Other&#x0201d; included roles such as empowerment of children (particularly girls), development of new hospitals, monitoring of existing eye camps, and involvement in new technology. Additionally, all of the respondents had at least 5 years of experience providing eye care services in rural areas, with 27% having over 20 years of experience. Almost all respondents were directly involved in cataract surgeries and the majority also work in other specialized fields of ophthalmology, such as retina and glaucoma surgery [<xref rid="APP2" ref-type="app">Appendix B</xref>].</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Details about the place of practice:</italic> All experts (<italic toggle="yes">n</italic> = 22) interviewed worked in high-volume hospitals that serve as models of tertiary eye care delivery with outreach to rural and peri-urban areas on an intermittent basis [<xref rid="APP1" ref-type="app">Appendix A</xref>]. Outreach programs include comprehensive exams and refraction and referral to vision centers or tertiary centers for medical or surgical treatment if needed. These models provide free services to those who cannot afford them and paid services to support and sustain the free services.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Perspectives about resource availability and quality:</italic> Survey participants were generally satisfied or very satisfied with the tools at their disposal for pre-operative screening and in the operating theater [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F1" ref-type="fig">Fig. 1</xref>]. The trends also showed that participants were dissatisfied with the larger-scale resources at their institution, such as space, manpower, and anesthesia facilities [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F1" ref-type="fig">Fig. 1</xref>]. <xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F1" ref-type="fig">Fig. 1</xref> presents a detailed breakdown of various resources and expert perspectives on the value of these resources.</p><fig position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F1"><label>Figure 1</label><caption><p>Satisfaction and adequacy of resources: 19 of 22 survey respondents answered these questions regarding their perspectives on the quality of the resources at their disposal (space, manpower, surgical tools, screening tools, anesthesia and critical care facilities, and ambulance services) in the field of eye care in rural and periurban settings. More than 60% agree that microscopes and lighting are essential for quality eye care, and more than 70% agree that surgical tools in the operating theater are essential for quality eye care</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="IJO-72-473-g001" position="float"/></fig><p><italic toggle="yes">Perspectives about current cataract surgery practices</italic>: With cataract surgery as the prototype model for comparison between care delivery across different models, the survey questions were designed to understand the workflow for pre-operative, intra-operative, and post-operative processes. <xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-T1" ref-type="table">Table 1</xref> illustrates the current practices with overlapping spectrum amidst the differences across various models.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2196_23-T1"><label>Table 1</label><caption><p>Spectrum of workflow process based on pre-operative, intra-operative, and post-operative cataract care pathway across various models based on available resources</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cataract care pathway</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Ideal model</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Current models</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Pre-operative (cataract or any other form of surgery or procedure)</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Strict standardized lean protocols were validated to ensure they don&#x02019;t affect the quality of care. Changes to the protocol in changing gowns and dressing the patient to keep lower costs were made.</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Heterogenous models with a lack of standardized protocol&#x02014;ranging from torch light examination to slit lamp examination with and without dilated fundus exam. Pre-operative counseling advice to patients is not a norm and more often the patient and family do not receive counseling before surgery. However, some models do counseling once a patient agrees to surgery and perform biometry, blood pressure, blood sugar, and history of systemic diseases and workup as necessary.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Intra-operative workflow (cataract surgery)</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Patients who cannot afford to pay for their surgery receive manual small incision cataract surgery with rigid intraocular lens (IOL). Those who can pay receive phacoemulsification with the type of foldable IOL they want. Surgeries are done by experienced surgeons (or by trainee surgeons under the supervision of experienced surgeons) and in state-of-the-art operating theatres with standby equipments to manage complications like posterior capsular rent and trained operating theatre assistants. Outcomes are monitored to ensure that there are no any major differences. A strict quality outcome analysis/audit is in place where reporting of intraoperative complications is mandatory.</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Type of surgery and consumables is based on the patient&#x02019;s socioeconomic status. Emphasis is on the number of surgeries rather than the outcome. An example of this is using two tables with one microscope to adjust the time, microscope cost, and space in the operating room. Less experienced/junior doctors (unsupervised) and nurses are used due to the unavailability of experienced surgeons and nurses. There are often compromises in some steps of the surgery (such as cortical matter removal, management of complications like posterior capsular rupture, and descement&#x02019;s membrane detachment). No mandatory reporting of complications or outcomes of the surgery.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Post-operative workflow</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Follow a standardized protocol for post-operative management and evaluation. If there are intra-operative complications, they have different follow-up protocols. Patients are typically followed up on day 1 and at 4&#x02013;5 weeks, but if there are any complications or unexpected post-operative outcomes on day 1, patients are seen at week 1 or earlier. Every outreach camp includes both pre-operative screening and post-operative follow-up. Strict monitoring of the post-operative patients and follow-up rate and reporting of the complications and non-compliance (if any); typically the follow-up rate is 85&#x02013;90%. Also, there is a standardized protocol and script (with or without video-based instructions in the local language) in place for clear post-operative care/instructions and also conveyance in place to ensure patients are been sent to their towns in village/rural areas. The post-operative patients are also followed up at their homes/in town through locally trained healthcare workers in the community.</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Heterogenous protocols for post-operative evaluation based on available resources: Either done by trained or semi-trained doctors or healthcare workers. Ranging from torch light examination to slit lamp examination, care is based on bed occupancy&#x02014;patients are either discharged from the hospital on the same day of operation or kept overnight. The patients get instructions in groups about the post-operative care. Not mandatory or common to have videos/posters or community workers explain the postoperative care. The patients are sent home either by themselves or through hospital vehicles with a hospital team and are not necessarily monitored for one week or one month. Patients by themselves or through the help of community workers are brought to the hospital for glass appointments (glasses) at one to two months following surgery.</td></tr></tbody></table><table-wrap-foot><fn id="TF-F1"><p>*Ideal model: An ideal model proposed by authors based on experts&#x02019; perspectives. *Current models: The current models of eye care delivery in the community</p></fn></table-wrap-foot></table-wrap><p><italic toggle="yes">Perspectives about potential complications and iatrogenic blindness following cataract surgery:</italic> Based on the survey responses, participants generally believed that novice surgeons with a lack of training and delayed presentation causing higher grades of cataracts were the most common reasons for a higher incidence of complications in rural settings. A lack of transportation facilities and lack of awareness among patients indirectly leads to presenting at a later cataract stage and delayed presentation of post-operative patients with complications (post-operative endophthalmitis, iris prolapse, intraocular lens dislocation) at irreversible stages and accounting for iatrogenic blindness. Some other factors mentioned that may increase complication rates were poor patient hygiene and long-standing traumatic cataracts associated with poor socioeconomic conditions, faulty and unsupervised pre-operative screening and sterilization procedures, and malpractice from quacks.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Perspectives about the various eye care models for rural communities</italic>: The eye care model perspectives part of the survey demonstrated that 87% of participants agreed with providing primary eye care services in rural/peri-urban areas [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F2" ref-type="fig">Fig. 2</xref>]. Likewise, more than 60% of the experts were not in agreement with the makeshift center model of eye care delivery. The &#x0201c;makeshift center&#x0201d; model of delivery of eye care services involves building temporary hospitals and surgical centers in local places such as schools or community centers. There was a wide range of opinions regarding the makeshift center model of eye care delivery, with approximately equal numbers (percentage/ratio) of physicians indicating strongly disagree, neutral, and strongly agree. The &#x0201c;fly-in fly-out&#x0201d; model of eye care delivery is when physicians from foreign countries or outside the region come to perform surgeries for a few days and then leave. The majority of respondents either agreed or were neutral about this type of eye care delivery, as they believed that occasionally when physicians from other institutions come to perform surgeries, there is a lot to learn from their surgical practice. However, the downside is that there must be a proper system in place to ensure the follow-up of those patients, or else their post-operative care will be neglected. Thus, there were no participants who indicated &#x0201c;strongly agree&#x0201d; because the feasibility and sustainability of ensuring quality care with the fly-in fly-out model is low.</p><fig position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F2"><label>Figure 2</label><caption><p>Eye care delivery perspectives: Survey respondents were asked about their opinions on three prominent eye care delivery models (fly-in/fly-out, makeshift centers, and tertiary eye care hospitals supported by primary eye care outreach camps). They were asked whether they strongly agreed, agreed, were neutral, disagreed, or strongly disagreed with those three eye care delivery models</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="IJO-72-473-g002" position="float"/></fig><p><italic toggle="yes">Perspective about engaging community healthcare workers:</italic>
<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F2" ref-type="fig">Fig. 2</xref> demonstrates that most experts generally agreed that involving community-based workers and incentivizing them will be beneficial to the quality and sustainability of community ophthalmology practices. Based on survey responses, some ways to educate community health workers and change their attitudes toward adopting new methods or protocols are to provide periodic hands-on and practical workshops, refreshment classes, incentives through awards or conference presentations, and ensure that their work is facilitated with regular engagement to reduce frustration and unnecessary burden. The two main future technological advancements that the experts saw necessary to implement in rural eye care delivery models were electronic medical records for ease of documentation and telemedicine at outreach vision centers. Some systemic changes that could be made were to provide phacoemulsification to all cataract surgery patients, hire patient counselors, and promote more untold heroes of community ophthalmology to foster leadership and empathy.</p></sec><sec sec-type="discussion" id="sec1-3"><title>Discussion</title><p>The term &#x0201c;community ophthalmology&#x0201d; encompasses several components involved in the delivery of eye care in rural settings. This includes raising awareness of eye health in the community, conducting epidemiological research and community-based surveys, planning and management of comprehensive and sustainable eye care services, and training of primary eye care workers.[<xref rid="R7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref>] By surveying a number of physicians from less densely populated countries in Southeast Asia, we are hoping to better understand their perspective on delivering eye care to the community and the difficulties they face.[<xref rid="R8" ref-type="bibr">8</xref>] The semi-structured survey-based study will further enable us to gain a more holistic perspective on community ophthalmology in a wider range of rural settings beyond Southeast Asia. Our survey provided a broad range of opinions and insights regarding community ophthalmology that were used to direct the proposal of a more practical model of eye care delivery. As the experts participating in the survey had vast experience in primary eye care in rural settings, it provided further depth to the respondents&#x02019; breadth of knowledge.</p><p>Lack of resources including trained staff and the fragmented compromised cataract care pathway (pre-operative screening, intra-operative care, and post-operative care) can potentially result in iatrogenic blindness contributing to the burden of irreversible blindness.[<xref rid="R9" ref-type="bibr">9</xref>] Though the strengths of the temporary/makeshift center model are that it can benefit rural communities by bringing care directly to them, especially if it is solely primary eye care services where refractive correction can be provided instantly, for invasive eye care services, the surgical conditions such as sanitation, tools, equipment, and access to emergency care are less than ideal in makeshift centers, and this can pose serious medicolegal issues in some instances.[<xref rid="R10" ref-type="bibr">10</xref>] However, both the makeshift model, typically lacking essential infrastructure and standardized protocols, and the fly-in fly-out model, often facing challenges in sustainability and consistency, do not receive support from the regulatory system in India. This regulatory limitation is perceived to cause considerable obstacles to accessible eye care services across the country. In light of this, both the Indian and Nepal governments have put forward propositions for a primary and secondary eye care integration model that emphasizes the establishment of proper infrastructure and encourages public&#x02013;private partnerships (PPPs). This model aims to strengthen the accessibility and quality of eye care services, particularly in underserved rural areas where a majority of the populations in Southeast Asia reside and there is a much higher prevalence of vision impairment, fostering a more sustainable and inclusive approach to addressing the nation&#x02019;s eye care needs.</p><p>The experts believed that the biggest barriers to ensuring sustainable eye care delivery and positive patient outcomes in rural settings are retaining skilled surgeons,[<xref rid="R11" ref-type="bibr">11</xref>] lack of funding, infrastructure, patient awareness, and transportation.[<xref rid="R12" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>] Yet, sustainable eye care delivery requires empowering the local population, local eye care providers, optometrists,[<xref rid="R13" ref-type="bibr">13</xref>] and ophthalmologists[<xref rid="R14" ref-type="bibr">14</xref><xref rid="R15" ref-type="bibr">15</xref><xref rid="R16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>] with the necessary education and skills required to address the root causes of vision impairment and blindness through primary care that is ultimately initiated and sustained by the rural communities themselves. Sustainable eye care delivery would thus prompt us to consider laying the foundation for community eye care through providing affordable and sustainable technology, and resources, upskilling rural eye care providers, and educating the rural populations such that they would be able to sustain quality eye care in the long run without requiring external aid.</p><sec id="sec2-1"><title>Proposal of a practical eye care delivery model</title><p>The surveyed experts considered that the six most important components for an effective eye care delivery model are awareness, accessibility, affordability, equality in quality, &#x0201c;closing the circle&#x0201d;, and sustainability.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Awareness:</italic> Patient awareness of health issues and the importance of seeking care is the first step in providing eye care delivery. Training of local representatives aids in building trust and those workers serve as an example to others in their rural villages [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-T2" ref-type="table">Table 2</xref>]. Owing to many of the subsidized patients being illiterate, providing visual- and audio-based counseling in the local language will aid in improving awareness and patient education of preventable diseases such as diabetes. Awareness is key to the primary prevention of vision impairment and blindness since local populations would better understand how to practice good eye care at home and take note of symptoms to look out for that require eye screening.[<xref rid="R17" ref-type="bibr">17</xref><xref rid="R18" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>] For a PPP and an integrated care model, experts emphasized the need for joint awareness campaigns and community outreach programs in collaboration with both the government and private eye care institutions. They also stressed the importance of promoting awareness of the significance of regular eye check-ups in routine healthcare practices through joint programs between general healthcare providers and eye care specialists.</p><table-wrap position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2196_23-T2"><label>Table 2</label><caption><p>Key actions required to achieve the components of a practical model for eyecare delivery in the rural community</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Component</th><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Key actions</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Awareness</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Training of local representatives to serve as community ophthalmology workers promotes community involvement in the healthcare process.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Increased patient and public understanding of eye care through joint awareness campaigns by government and private institutions.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Enhanced community outreach programs in collaboration with private organizations to educate the public about eye care services and prevention.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Accessibility</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Develop purpose-built vision centers where all primary medical including diagnostic facilities are available except the surgical unit, with a robust referral mechanism in place.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Establishing more eye care clinics in rural and underserved areas through joint efforts of the government and private sector.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Providing mobile eye care units to reach remote areas, facilitated through joint investment and coordination.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Integrating eye care services into existing primary healthcare centers for easier access for the general population.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Implementing telemedicine for remote diagnosis and consultation, ensuring that people in distant locations have access to specialized eye care services.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Affordability</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Developing a healthcare management platform would allow total transparency in the system and at the same time provide a single open-source integrated platform for data tracking, data auditing, self-assessment tools for vision assessment, tracking cataract surgery screening, and surgical outcomes.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Offering subsidized or free eye care services through collaboration between the government and private institutions.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Setting up special funding programs for underprivileged communities to access eye care treatments through joint funding efforts.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Introducing comprehensive healthcare packages that include eye care services at subsidized rates within the general healthcare system.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Establishing community-based health insurance schemes that cover eye care services, thereby reducing financial burdens for the general population.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Equality in quality</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Strict guidelines and protocols should be followed to ensure that all patients are treated equally and to never compromise on patient care, regardless of whether they are paying or non-paying patients.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Ensuring standardization of care through collaborative guidelines and protocols for both public and private eye care providers.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Conducting regular quality assessments and audits to maintain consistent service quality across all partnered institutions.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Implementing unified standards and protocols for eye care services within the general healthcare system.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Providing continuous training and skill development programs for healthcare professionals to maintain consistent quality in eye care services across all healthcare settings.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Closing the circle</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Having a strong human resource team with patient care coordinators that properly counsel and educate patients on hygiene, administration of eye drops, what signs of complications to look out for, and where to locally seek care in the case of emergency complications.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Having patient counselors is crucial for convincing patients of the importance of returning for follow-up.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Providing dark glasses immediately after surgery, information pamphlets in the local language with drawings for illiterate patients, a phone number to call in case of emergencies, and appropriate refraction glasses for free before they leave the tertiary hospital are other ways to close the circle and give patients the certainty that they are receiving precise care.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Establishing mechanisms for continuous communication and feedback between public and private stakeholders to address gaps in the provision of eye care services.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Creating referral networks between primary healthcare centers and specialized eye care facilities for seamless patient transitions and follow-up care.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Developing integrated electronic health record systems that allow for the seamless sharing of patient information between general healthcare providers and eye care specialists.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Implementing regular follow-up protocols for patients undergoing eye care treatments to ensure continuity of care and monitor long-term outcomes.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Sustainability</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Continuous fundraising through corporate social responsibility and donors.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Increasing support and building trust from I-NGOs, N-NGOs, and other community financial supportive agencies.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Formulating long-term sustainable funding models for the maintenance and expansion of eye care services through joint investment strategies.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Encouraging research and development initiatives in collaboration with private entities to promote sustainable advancements in eye care technologies and treatments.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Incorporating environmental sustainability practices in the delivery of eye care services within the broader healthcare system.<break/>&#x02022;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;&#x000a0;Implementing training programs and capacity-building initiatives to ensure a sustainable workforce capable of meeting the growing demand for integrated eye care services.</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><p><italic toggle="yes">Accessibility:</italic> One of the main reasons for the delayed presentation of patients in rural areas to tertiary eye care centers is accessibility challenges.[<xref rid="R19" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>] Primary eye care services provided in makeshift vision camps or permanent vision centers in more peripheral rural areas must be backed by a tertiary center that provides surgery and required care for the patients [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-T2" ref-type="table">Table 2</xref>].[<xref rid="R20" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>] Primary eye care services in vision centers should be equipped with slit lamps and equipment necessary to minimize hospital visits and provide as many services as possible, such as screening and refraction services.[<xref rid="R21" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>] Optometrists and ophthalmologists in secondary centers should be trained at the tertiary centers and provide specialty care to vision centers via the portal of telemedicine. Certain diagnostic equipment such as hand-held non-mydriatic fundus cameras equipped with visual acuity applications and sturdy autorefractometer could be installed in a van to work like a mobile eye clinic and further improve primary care access to patients.[<xref rid="R22" ref-type="bibr">22</xref><xref rid="R23" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>] For the PPP and integrated care model, experts suggested the establishment of more eye care clinics in underserved areas, along with the provision of mobile eye care units facilitated through joint investments and coordination under the PPP model. Similarly, they proposed integrating eye care services into existing primary healthcare centers and implementing telemedicine for remote diagnosis and consultation under the integration model.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Affordability:</italic> The socioeconomic status of patients in rural areas is generally quite poor, so in order for the majority of patients from outreach camps to receive care, their surgeries need to be subsidized.[<xref rid="R24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref><xref rid="R25" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>] Therefore, it is crucial for eye care delivery models to have both paid and unpaid services. The paying patients essentially cover the cost of the services provided to unpaid patients, creating a self-sustaining hospital system. Implementing more government health insurance plans could also aid in increasing the affordability of eye care services. Also, structured partnerships with non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to support the funding requirements for centers operating in rural communities could be quite impactful. Experts emphasized the importance of offering subsidized or free eye care services through joint funding efforts and the establishment of special funding programs for underprivileged communities under the PPP model. They also stressed the significance of introducing comprehensive healthcare packages that include eye care services at subsidized rates within the general healthcare system and establishing community-based health insurance schemes like Ayushman Bharat under the integration model.[<xref rid="R26" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>]</p><p>We propose an open-source robust technology platform&#x02014;healthcare management platform (HMP)&#x02014;to allow transparency in the entire ecosystem without any pilferages [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F3" ref-type="fig">Fig. 3</xref>]. The proposed platform will allow (and should mandate) donors (including NGOs and govt organizations) to work with the possible partners/beneficiaries and that would hence establish accountability and credibility of both donors and beneficiaries.[<xref rid="R27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>] At the same time, this platform should allow other management and clinical purposes such as data tracking, data auditing, self-assessment tools for vision assessment, tracking cataract surgery screening, and surgical outcomes and complications, in the end, serving as a human-chain supply distribution system (HCSDS) [<xref rid="APP3" ref-type="app">Appendix C</xref>].</p><fig position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2196_23-F3"><label>Figure 3</label><caption><p>Healthcare management platform for integrated community ophthalmology work&#x02014;a proposed model/platform for eyecare delivery in rural/semi-urban settings</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="IJO-72-473-g003" position="float"/></fig><p><italic toggle="yes">Equality in quality:</italic> Many current models of eye care delivery provide manual small incision cataract surgery and rigid intraocular lenses for all subsidized surgeries, and only provide phacoemulsification to paying patients.[<xref rid="R25" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>] This should be standardized to allow all patients to receive the same surgery and lenses, depending on the grade of cataract[<xref rid="R28" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>] and not based on socioeconomic status.[<xref rid="R29" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>] If not completely practical, stringent outcome analysis must be performed to ensure quality is not being compromised between the two patient demographics. All patients should be treated as regular patients and there should not be a discrepancy between junior and senior consultants operating on poor or rich patients. So long as the scoring systems and technical hierarchies in place for case distributions are equitable and only based on the difficulty of the case, this is acceptable. There should also be thorough training systems in place to ensure all surgeons have adequate surgical skills and are exposed to enough time in the operating theatre.[<xref rid="R30" ref-type="bibr">30</xref><xref rid="R31" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>] Experts highlighted the need for standardized care through collaborative guidelines and protocols for both public and private eye care providers under the PPP model. They also stressed the importance of implementing unified standards and protocols for eye care services within the general healthcare system under the integration model. Participants emphasized the importance of establishing mechanisms for continuous communication and feedback between public and private stakeholders to address gaps in the provision of eye care services and create referral networks between primary healthcare centers and specialized eye care facilities for seamless patient transitions and follow-up care under the PPP model. They also stressed the significance of developing integrated electronic health record systems and implementing regular follow-up protocols for patients undergoing eye care treatments under the integration model.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Closing the circle:</italic> A major challenge in eye care in rural settings is ensuring proper follow-up of patients.[<xref rid="R32" ref-type="bibr">32</xref>] Closing the circle implies completing the full cycle of care from thorough pre-operative screening through 30-day post-operative follow-up.[<xref rid="R33" ref-type="bibr">33</xref>] Currently, many community eye care services that are being practiced do not have proper systems in place to ensure sufficient follow-up, and would greatly benefit from having a separate protocol and system in place solely to ensure proper follow-up. This is essential in maintaining the initial intention for quality eye care through treatment, without which many of the treatments provided would be futile and even counter-effective. Several strategies listed in <xref rid="IJO.IJO_2196_23-T2" ref-type="table">Table 2</xref> could be helpful in achieving this goal.</p><p><italic toggle="yes">Sustainability:</italic> Funding is always a challenge for any institution, particularly for organizations in rural settings. Operation expenditures can be made to be self-sustaining through a model with both paying and non-paying patients. Continuous fundraising through corporate social responsibility and donors may be necessary to build peripheral centers and new hospitals. Increasing support and building trust from I-NGOs, N-NGOs, and other community financial supportive agencies is important, as they may prioritize the existing eye care delivery systems for collaboration and keep the newly emerging hospitals or smaller eye care delivery units on stand-by.[<xref rid="R14" ref-type="bibr">14</xref><xref rid="R34" ref-type="bibr">34</xref>] One of the biggest challenges of establishing a hospital in rural areas is the sustainability of human resources and skilled doctors in these sorts of locations.[<xref rid="R35" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>] Experts suggested formulating long-term sustainable funding models for the maintenance and expansion of eye care services through joint investment strategies under the PPP model. Similarly, they emphasized the importance of implementing training programs and capacity-building initiatives to ensure a sustainable workforce capable of meeting the growing demand for integrated eye care services under the integration model.</p><p>Besides developing a practical and robust model for eyecare delivery, experts believe social capital is a crucial component in generating community support and participation for joint awareness campaigns and rural community outreach programs, thus enhancing the dissemination of information about the importance of regular eye check-ups and overall eye care services to previously uninformed patients. Empowering patients and improving their social capital by teaching them about the factors that contribute to better health have the potential to transform patient lifestyles, reduce eye diseases, and benefit public health in these rural communities. Survey participants also emphasized the role of social capital in fostering partnerships and collaborations between different stakeholders, including government bodies, private institutions, and community-based organizations, to ensure the accessibility, affordability, and sustainability of eye care services in remote and underserved areas. Social capital was viewed as a catalyst for the mobilization of resources and the coordination of efforts to establish more eye care clinics and mobile units, particularly in areas with limited healthcare access.</p></sec></sec><sec sec-type="conclusion" id="sec1-4"><title>Conclusion</title><p>In conclusion, HCSDS-HMP modelled by the six components suggested by experts could be a solution for effective rural eye care delivery. These components include awareness, accessibility, affordability, equality in quality, closing the circle, and sustainability, and involve a series of concrete actions to be achieved. By implementing these measures and leveraging on social capital, we can strive toward a future where community care is not just a goal but a reality, positively impacting the lives of all individuals in the long run.</p><sec id="sec2-2"><title>Authorship statement</title><p>ICMJE criteria were used for inclusion in the authors&#x02019; list. The manuscript has been read and approved by all the authors, all authors contributed substantially to this work and met the ICMJE criteria for authorship, and each author believes that the manuscript represents honest work.</p></sec><sec id="sec2-3"><title>Contribution details</title><p>Concept and design: Rupesh Agrawal, Alok Sen, Lucia Sobrin. Definition of intellectual content: Rupesh Agrawal, Hugh Taylor, Rohit C Khanna, Chitaranjan Mishra, Anna CS Tan, Alok Sen, Lucia Sobrin. Data acquisition: Ashita Ashish Sule, Thulasiraj Ravilla. Data analysis, and statistical analysis: Renee Liu. Results interpretation: All the authors. Manuscript preparation: Renee Liu, Choo Sheriel Shannon, William Rojas-Carabali. Manuscript editing and manuscript review: All the authors.</p></sec><sec sec-type="funding-statement" id="sec2-4"><title>Financial support and sponsorship</title><p>Nil.</p></sec><sec sec-type="COI-statement" id="sec2-5"><title>Conflicts of interest</title><p>There are no conflicts of interest.</p></sec></sec></body><back><ref-list><title>References</title><ref id="R1"><label>1.</label><element-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author">
