</element-citation></ref></ref-list><app-group><app id="APP1"><title>Appendix A: (A1) Drafts and final version of a semi-structured survey questionnaire. It consists of close-ended and open-ended questions, finalized with the inputs of global healthcare experts. (A2) Geographical locations of experts from India in Nepal who participated in the survey</title><p>
<bold>Appendix A1:</bold>
</p><p>
<bold>Community Ophthalmology Perspective Survey V2</bold>
</p><p>A survey questionnaire to understand the intent, the need and the impact of community ophthalmology particularly in rural and peri-urban areas.</p><p>
<bold>Details about the survey:</bold>
</p><p>This survey based study aims to understand the current practices and global perspectives surrounding the intent, need, and impact of eye care services particularly in rural and peri-urban settings.</p><p>We define community ophthalmology using the WHO's definition of &#x0201c;the term used for the promotion and protection of eye health, and the provision of eye care, at the community level&#x0201d; and &#x0201c;is based on the concepts of public health ophthalmology, emphasizing particularly the interface between providers and consumers of eye care, and the empowering of communities to improve eye health&#x0201d;.</p><p>This survey aims to explore what we are currently doing to provide primary, secondary, and tertiary community eye care in rural and peri-urban areas, and what are the future directions needed to improve patient outcomes and implement sustainable eye care delivery systems in those areas.</p><p>Peri-urban areas are defined by UNESCO as &#x0201c;zones of transition from rural to urban land uses located between the outer limits of urban and regional centers and the rural environment.&#x0201d;</p><p>According to the WHO, primary level eye care involves community-based workers identifying and refering people with low vision to a higher level of service and advice on environmental modification. Secondary level eye care is at the district-level and involves assessing visual function, refraction testing, prescribing low-vision devices, and providing guidance on optical interventions and referring to tertiary services when appropriate. Tertiary level eye care involves a team of trained professionals offering advanced care in a highly developed eye clinic or hospital.</p><p>Through this survey, we hope to understand variance in practice patterns in different regions of the world, and determine what are some standard guidelines we can develop to help more people in the community and reduce blindness due to over-intervention. This would enable us to propose a revised and more practical model for eye care providers and policy makers to refer to while providing eye care services in rural and peri-urban areas in the future.</p><p>Please find here a <underline>list of references</underline> if you would like more literature about community ophthalmology.</p><p>All the experts (participants) should read the following before proceeding with the survey.</p><list list-type="order"><list-item><p>You have been identified to participate in this study to assess your experience and perceptions of community ophthalmology in rural areas.</p></list-item><list-item><p>This may be administered as either an interview-based or online survey. Participation is purely voluntary.</p></list-item><list-item><p>Your name and geographical location will be collected to understand your geographical region of community ophthalmology work and also for publication purposes.</p></list-item><list-item><p>This survey will take approximately 60 minutes to complete. You will be acknowledged as an interview participant and expert in the introductory paragraph of the publication resulting from this survey.</p></list-item><list-item><p>All data collected will be solely used for the purpose of research and is not part of participants' standard clinical care.</p></list-item><list-item><p>By participating in this study, participants agree to allow all data provided to be used by the investigators and study team for research purposes.</p></list-item></list><p>
<bold>Name</bold>
</p><p>
<inline-graphic xlink:href="IJO-72-473-g004.jpg"/>
</p><p>
