</p><p>
<bold>Appendix C2:</bold>
</p><p>
<bold>Factors affecting the outcome of cataract surgery in rural settings</bold>
</p><p>Real world study to look into the factors resulting in poor post operative outcome following cataract surgery</p><p>
<bold>Introduction:</bold>
</p><p>Unaddressed cataract remains the most prevalent cause of moderate or severe distance vision impairment or blindness worldwide, affecting more than 94 million people globally. Particularly amongst the low and middle-income regions, the incidence of distance vision impairment is quadruple that of high-income regions. In India alone, the WHO/NPCB survey estimated a backlog of over 11 million blind people, of which an overwhelming 80.1% of these blindness are caused by cataract. Currently, cataract surgery remains the only definitive treatment of cataract-induced vision impairment. Nevertheless, many studies have reported poor visual outcomes amongst 30-40% of the patients who have undertaken cataract surgery, defined by poor visual acuities which are inadequate to meet the needs of daily activities. It is thus paramount to examine if patients are attaining the best possible visual outcomes after cataract surgery, and investigate the preoperative, intraoperative and postoperative factors predisposing to poor visual outcomes post-surgery. We are hence conducting a real world observational study to explore the factors contributing to poor post operative visual outcome following a cataract surgery.</p><p>
<bold>Objectives:</bold>
</p><list list-type="order"><list-item><p>To study and analyze the pre-op and intra-op factors affecting the outcome in patients undergoing cataract surgery in rural settings.</p></list-item><list-item><p>To validate the visual acuity and contrast sensitity application based on novel PocDoc platform.</p></list-item></list><p>
<bold>Rationale for the Study Population:</bold>
</p><p>The study includes a population recruited from the patients presenting to eye clinics at hospitals with cataract disease. Recruitment is regardless of participant's race, age and gender to obtain a demographic more representative of India's general population. The subjects will be recruited from eye clinics due to easy access to high patient load, with an appropriate setting to explain any risks and benefits of this study. Waiver of informed consent form will be obtained for this observational study.</p><p>
